  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Suwon's Cloud-Brocade Tower
  author: Seol Mun-u
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The tower rises within layered emerald forests—
    One climb, and gazing out, the four directions open wide.
    Among the flowers, blue tiles overlap like scales,
    Upon the stones, moss patterns speckle rosy red.
    Reclining on my pillow, rain drums on lotus leaves,
    As the breeze stirs willow branches dancing past my curtain.
    Exiled here, yet everywhere the rivers and mountains gleam—
    All things follow the old sage's tale: fortune lost, fortune gained.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The 'Cloud-Brocade Tower' (雲錦樓) likely refers to a pavilion in Suwon known for its panoramic views, with 'cloud-brocade' evoking the interplay of mist and landscape coloring.
  - key: ''
    value: The final couplet alludes to the folk tale of the Old Man of Sai, who teaches acceptance of life's reversals through the famous line 'when one door closes, another opens'—suggesting the poet finds wisdom in apparent misfortune.
  - key: ''
    value: The poem employs the conceit of exile as a spiritual journey, transforming banishment into an occasion for contemplating natural beauty and philosophical acceptance.
